✅ 1. Install OpenSSH Server (on BOTH VMs)
Run PowerShell as Administrator:
PowerShell
Get-WindowsCapability -Online | Where-Object Name -like 'OpenSSH.Server*'
If not installed:
PowerShell
Add-WindowsCapability -Online -Name OpenSSH.Server~~~~0.0.1.0
✅ 2. Start and Enable SSH Service
PowerShell
Start-Service sshd
Set-Service -Name sshd -StartupType Automatic
Verify:
PowerShell
Get-Service sshd
Status should be Running
✅ 3. Allow SSH in Firewall
PowerShell
New-NetFirewallRule -Name sshd -DisplayName "OpenSSH Server" `
-Enabled True -Direction Inbound -Protocol TCP -Action Allow -LocalPort 22
✅ 4. Check SSH Config (IMPORTANT)
Open file:

C:\ProgramData\ssh\sshd_config
Make sure these lines are set:
Plain text
Port 22
PermitRootLogin yes
PasswordAuthentication yes
⚠️ For Windows:
"root" = Administrator
You login using Windows account
After editing:
PowerShell
Restart-Service sshd
✅ 5. Test from Master → Slave
From 192.168.119.128 (Master):
Bash
ssh Administrator@192.168.119.129
✅ 6. Verify Network (CRITICAL)
Before SSH, check:
Bash
ping 192.168.119.129
If ping fails → SSH will NEVER work.
🚨 Common Issues (Based on your previous errors)
❌ 1. "Ping timeout"
→ Network not connected / wrong adapter
✔ Fix:
Use Bridged Adapter (same network) OR same NAT network
Both VMs must be in same subnet (you already are ✔)
❌ 2. Static IP breaks network
→ You likely didn’t set Gateway + DNS
Example config:
Field
Value
IP
192.168.119.128
Subnet
255.255.255.0
Gateway
192.168.119.1
❌ 3. SSH timeout
→ Usually firewall or sshd not running
Check:
PowerShell
netstat -an | findstr :22
Should show LISTENING